<font color="#FF0000">ART OF THE EXPLITIVE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan 30 22:54:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Until recently, I didn't respond much other than to acknowledge that I had been there.  The environment was such that there was a very negative connotation to even the comment that I had been there.  Now I'm finding that people are much more open to the expression of opinion, the ability to tell some of what happened, and the feeling that it will be accepted by at least some of the people I talk to.  <br><br>
On the other hand, there are those who are still very caught not only in the emotions, but also in their own entrenched position. I recently wrote an article on the war which was titled &quot;Real heroes of Vietnam too often still nameless.&quot; It was published in the March 19, 1996 edition of the Oregonian newspaper and was really a followup on an article a former protester wrote wondering why there were no memorials to protesters.  I received a very interesting mixed bag of letters from veterans and former protesters, showing that the emotions of this war are far from over.<br><br>
As others have stated in various dialog strings here, we have just begun scratching the surface of feelings and meanings that &quot;Vietnam&quot; brings to each of us.<br><br>
Mike, your talk of the use of explitives is appropriate, and don't think we are trying to put you on the defensive. No justification is necessary; mine was only a cautionary note.<br><br>
For the rest of the public, and those following these conversations, let me tell a story here to illustrate what Mike was saying.  <br><br>
An American pilot had been shot down in North Vietnam. Our rescue forces were on their way into his landing site, homing on his radio beacon, when the Jolly Green pilot asked the downed pilot to &quot;authenicate.&quot; Here's a guy who's just been shot down, made his first parachute jump in years, starting at 500 mph+, landed in trees, has enemy troops closing in on his position, and some yahoo pilot for air rescue is trying to get him to remember his authenication code. He can't, and promptly tells the Jolly pilot that he'd better come in and get him because the @#W$#%$## enemy was *&amp;)_&amp;*_&amp;_&amp;_&amp; and about to @@#$#%$#%$##%$#%$. In short, he cussed up a storm.  The Jolly pilot told the downed pilot, &quot;We're coming in!&quot; and they made the rescue.<br><br>

